03901nam a22004815i 9780887553899DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20052005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875538997 a10.1515/97808875538992doi  a(DE-B1597)664636  a(OCoLC)1408682420  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aLIT0040602bisacsh04a810.900aTravelling Knowledges :bPositioning the Im/Migrant Reader of Aboriginal Literatures in Canada. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (274 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tComing to Theory -- tBridging the Gap or Squaring the Circle? A Retrospective -- tRoutes or Roots? -- tThe Rhetoric of Mobility -- tAn Ethics of Reading -- tPositioning the Immigrant Critic -- tThe Question of Cultural Literacy -- tReading for Boundary De/Constructions -- tContextualizing the Other -- tThe Problem of Essentializing -- tReading for Movement and Migration -- tColonial Boundaries, De-Colonial Movements -- tMoving Between Cultures, Languages, and Literacies -- tTravelling Knowledges -- tThe "Trickster’s" Wanderlust and the Continuum of Reading -- tThe Quest for Identity -- tThe Global Search for Truth and Justice -- tConclusion -- tEndnotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the context of de/colonization, the boundary between an Aboriginal text and the analysis by a non-Aboriginal outsider poses particular challenges often constructed as unbridgeable. Eigenbrod argues that politically correct silence is not the answer but instead does a disservice to the literature that, like all literature, depends on being read, taught, and disseminated in various ways. In Travelling Knowledges, Eigenbrod suggests decolonizing strategies when approaching Aboriginal texts as an outsider and challenges conventional notions of expertise. She concludes that literatures of colonized peoples have to be read ethically, not only without colonial impositions of labels but also with the responsibility to read beyond the text or, in Lee Maracle's words, to become "the architect of great social transformation." Features the works of: Jeannette Armstrong (Okanagan), Louise Halfe (Cree), Margo Kane (Saulteaux/Cree), Maurice Kenny (Mohawk), Thomas King (Cherokee, living in Canada), Emma LaRocque (Cree/Metis), Lee Maracle (Sto:lo/Metis), Ruby Slipperjack (Anishnaabe), Lorne Simon (Miíkmaq), Richard Wagamese (Anishnaabe), and Emma Lee Warrior (Peigan).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Native American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755389940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553899/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles